SIMPLE: flap
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flap
<hw>Flap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>flappe</ets>,
<ets>flap</ets>, blow, bly-flap; cf. D. <ets>flap</ets>, and E.
<ets>flap</ets>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>Anything broad and limber
that hangs loose, or that is attached by one side or end and is easily
moved; <as>as, the <ex>flap</ex> of a garment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A cartilaginous <qex>flap</qex> upon the opening of the
larynx.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hinged leaf, as of a table or shutter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The motion of anything broad and loose, or a stroke
or sound made with it; <as>as, the <ex>flap</ex> of a sail or of a
wing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>A disease in the
lips of horses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Aeronautics)</fld> <def>a movable part of an
airplane wing, used to increase lift or drag, especially when taking off
or landing. used often in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flap tile</b></col>, <cd>a tile with a bent up portion,
to turn a corner or catch a drip.</cd> -- <col><b>Flap valve</b></col>
<fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a valve which opens and shuts upon one hinged
side; a clack valve.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flap
<hw>Flap</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Flapped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flapping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prob. of imitative
origin; cf. D. <ets>flappen</ets>, E. <ets>flap</ets>, <pos>n.</pos>,
flop, flippant, fillip.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To beat with a flap; to
strike.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet let me <qex>flap</qex> this bug with gilded wings.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move, as something broad and flaplike; <as>as, to
<ex>flap</ex> the wings</as>; to let fall, as the brim of a
hat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To flap in the mouth</b></col>, <cd>to taunt.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>W. Cartwright.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flap
<hw>Flap</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move as do wings, or
as something broad or loose; to fly with wings beating the
air.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The crows <qex>flapped</qex> over by twos and threes.</q>
<rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fall and hang like a flap, as the brim of a hat,
or other broad thing.</def> <rj><au>Gay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flapdragon</ent>⟦br⟧
